  <h1>What to Do After a Civil Rights Violation</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>1. Document everything immediately</h2>
  <p>Write a detailed account of what happened: date, time, location, identity of officers or officials (badge numbers, names if possible), exactly what was said and done, witnesses present, and your injuries. If you were physically injured, photograph injuries as soon as possible &mdash; document them before they heal. Video recordings of police encounters are legal in all states and can be decisive evidence.</p>
  <h2>2. Seek medical attention</h2>
  <p>If physically injured, seek medical treatment immediately. Medical records establish the existence and severity of injuries. Gaps in medical treatment can be used by defendants to minimize damages. Emergency room and urgent care records are often the first contemporaneous documentation of injuries.</p>
  <h2>3. Preserve all evidence</h2>
  <p>Do not delete phone recordings, text messages, or social media posts related to the incident. Request body camera footage and incident reports from law enforcement promptly &mdash; many jurisdictions have limited retention periods (30&ndash;90 days). Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) or state equivalents can compel production. Surveillance footage from nearby businesses should be requested quickly.</p>
  <h2>4. No pre-suit administrative exhaustion required</h2>
  <p>Unlike employment discrimination claims, &sect; 1983 claims generally do not require filing with any administrative agency before suing. However, some states require notice-of-claim filings (often within 90&ndash;180 days) before suing government entities &mdash; missing these deadlines can bar the claim even if the statute of limitations hasn&rsquo;t run.</p>
  <h2>5. Find a civil rights attorney quickly</h2>
  <p>Section 1983 cases require attorneys experienced in civil rights litigation, qualified immunity doctrine, and Monell claims. The statute of limitations is typically 2&ndash;3 years from the violation, but notice-of-claim requirements in many states are much shorter. Consult a civil rights attorney as soon as possible. Most take these cases on contingency.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-section-1983-works">how section 1983 works</a> and <a href="/guides/common-civil-rights-misconceptions">common civil rights misconceptions</a>.</p>
